Commentary.Commentary: It is over to the visitors' batters now to do the job. They haven't been that great so far and to add to that, the wicket seems to have started playing tricks. Their batting line-up does not seem that strong with the absentees of a few top players so it is a chance for the ones who have come in to prove their mettle. Can they do so against an excellent Australian bowling attack? Join us in a bit to find out.

For the Kiwis, their problem has been they are unable to take wickets at regular intervals. They take one, then there is a partnership formed, they take another one and then there is another partnership due to which they are always behind the 8-ball game. Also, they picked two spinners for this game and both were quite disappointing. They did take three wickets in total but it was towards the end and they were also a tad expensive. Colin de Grandhomme once again impressed and Wagner like always bowled his heart. Overall, it is not a performance the Kiwis will be happy with.

That�s the end of another excellent performance by the Australians with the bat. Once again Tim Paine�s decision to bat first has been justified. Once again they were successful in stringing partnerships after partnerships. One big one between Smith and Labuschagne which accounted for over 150 and a few handy ones around the 50-run mark. Also, quite a few batters for them got off to starts, they needed someone to bat long and make that start count, Labuschagne did so. A marathon innings by him which saw Australia head into a commanding position.

OUT! Caught and bowled! An innings of high caliber comes to an end in a soft, soft manner. Probably the first mistake Labuschagne commits and he falls. He too can't believe it as he stands there in disgust and then starts walking off. All the Kiwi players rush up to him and shake his hand. The crowd is giving him a standing ovation as he makes his way back. Astle is the man who gets him. This was smart bowling. He bowled a googly on the last ball and this time he bowls a leg spinner on off. Labuschagne does not pick. He feels it is another googly and hence, looks to work it with the turn towards long on but it sticks in the wicket and also turns away a little. Labuschagne ends up chipping it back towards the bowler who takes it with a leap. Can New Zealand now take the remaining three wickets quickly?

We are back for the second session. The New Zealand players are out in the middle. Marnus Labuschagne and Tim Paine will resume their innings for the hosts. Neil Wagner will start the proceedings for the second session.
... Day 2, Session 2 ...

A good session for both the sides but Australia have dragged themselves in a good position. They though lost Wade early but Head and Labuschagne continued. They two put up another handy stand before Travis Head departed. Paine and Labuschagne are now at the crease and you would expect them to play an attacking brand of cricket after the break. The latter will be eyeing a double ton and Paine will hope they can finish somewhere close to the 500-run mark. For the Kiwis, they need to keep chipping away at the wickets. Can they do so? We will find out in sometime.

We are all set to begin Day 2. The New Zealand players are out in the middle. Marnus Labuschagne and Matthew Wade will resume their innings for the hosts. William Somerville will start the proceedings for New Zealand.

A brilliant ton by Labuschagne sees the hosts hold the edge after Day 1. Another solid stand will see them post a big first innings score. There is still a lot of batting to come and Australia will be aiming for a score after which they would only need to bat first. New Zealand on the other hand, need wickets early, they would somehow want to restrict the hosts to below 350. The ball is relatively new and they would want to make use of it. Can they do so? An important hour of play awaits. Stay tuned.
... Day 2, Session 1 ...

Now what will the two teams be hoping for on Day 2? Australia - they would want to bat as long as possible and post a big first innings score. New Zealand on the other hand, need wickets quickly or it could be yet another long day in the field for them. Do join us for all the action on Day 2 at 1030 local (2330 GMT, Previous Day). Till then, take care and goodbye!

Earlier in the day, after winning the toss and electing to bat, the Aussies once again lost Burns for not a lot. Warner and Labuschagne then put up a good stand but could not make it count for a lot. Smith and Marnus though made it big, the two accounted for over 150 and laid the foundation for a big first innings score. Labuschagne got to yet another ton, Smith look all set for one before he poked at a delivery outside off. Wade though has come out with a positive mindset and he would also want to make the start he has got count.

The last session too belonged to the hosts, once again they lost just the one wicket and managed to add around 100 runs. After the Tea interval, Smith and Labuschagne continued in their own merry way. They stretched their partnership to 150 and both just did not look like getting out. However, the second new ball then did the trick for the visitors as Colin de Grandhomme, their best bowler on Day 1 got Smith. Wade though ensured there were no more wickets to fall, also, he managed to score some quick runs towards the end and him along with Marnus are building another good stand.

End of a dominant day with the bat for Australia. Their star, Marnus Labuschagne walks off to a standing ovation. He deserves every bit of it, an excellent innings, full of class and it is because of him Australia are in the position they are in.

David Warner says they put us under a little pressure at the start as the ball was moving around but they went through that and are happy to build a good partnership. He hopes they can continue.

New Zealand on the other hand, will be a tad disappointed to get only the one wicket. The ball did do a bit at the start but they were a touch short. Colin de Grandhomme was probably the pick and the only wicket taker. The Kiwis need a few quick wickets after the break or they will be staring down a big first innings score. Do join us for the second session in a while but for now David Warner is giving an interview.

We are all set to begin. The New Zealand players are out in the middle. David Warner and Joe Burns will open the batting for Australia. Both the teams are seen wearing black arm bands in honor of the fire and emergency personnel who have been dealing with bushfires raging across Australia. Also, the numbers on the back of the Aussies are written in pink as it is the Pink Test. For New Zealand, Matt Henry will be starting proceedings for the visitors. Here we go...

Breaking News - A number of changes for the visitors however the biggest of them all is their skipper, Kane Williamson not playing. That is a huge blow, he hasn�t been amongst the runs but it is still a big miss.

NEW ZEALAND (PLAYING XI) - Tom Latham (C), Tom Blundell, Jeet Raval (In for Kane Williamson), Ross Taylor, Glenn Phillips (DEBUT) (In for Henry Nicholls), Colin de Grandhomme, BJ Watling (WK), William Somerville (In for Mitchell Santner), Todd Astle (In for Tim Southee), Neil Wagner, Matt Henry (In for Trent Boult).
AUSTRALIA (UNCHANGED PLAYING XI) - David Warner, Joe Burns, Marnus Labuschagne, Steven Smith, Matthew Wade, Travis Head, Tim Paine (WK/C), James Pattinson, Pat Cummins, Mitchell Starc, Nathan Lyon.
TOSS - Up goes the coin and it lands in favour of the hosts. Australia have won the toss and have opted to bat first.

Hello and a warm welcome to the third and the final Test of the series between Australia and New Zealand. With the series already won by the hosts, is this a dead rubber? Well, with the Test championship going on, don�t think any game is a dead rubber. Also, the home side will be eager to inflict a whitewash on their opponents whereas the visitors will be keen to end the series on a high. It has been too easy for Australia so far, can the Kiwis put up a better show?

Now then, Australia already lead by 203, there are a little more than 2 days to go so you would expect them to bat for at least three sessions, unless they are bowled out that is. The hosts would want to take the lead upto the 400-run mark before letting the Kiwis bat again. New Zealand on the other hand, will try and not let the Aussies score quickly and also manage to take wickets on regular intervals. Around 21 overs left in the day, it will be interesting to see how it pans out.

The Kiwis on the other hand, put in a better performance with the bat than they have done in the first innings of the previous few Tests. Still not an effort they would be very happy with. They had numerous number of stands which got off to starts but none significant. Also, quite a few batters got themselves in but nobody could make it count. Phillips was their top scorer with a half ton. However, when you are gunning down something more than 400, you need someone to get a ton and the rest to bat around him but that was not the case.

Another very good bowling performance from the Aussies! It was led by their offie, Nathan Lyon, who bagged a fifer. The wicket was assisting the spinners, he was expected to do the job with the ball and has delivered. He was well supported by Pat Cummins who had important wickets to his name. He grabbed a three-fer. No wickets to show for Pattinson and Starc had the one wicket to his name. Overall a good performance by the hosts.

However, his job is only half done and he needs to make it big here. He gets there in style. Pulls this short ball behind square on the leg side and bags another boundary.

We are back for the final session of Day 3. The Australian players are out in the middle. Glenn Phillips and Todd Astle will resume their innings for the visitors. Mitchell Starc will start the proceedings for the final session and Australia have taken the second new ball.
... Day 3, Session 3 ...

Pat Cummins says it was a good session for them, it is tough to score and he hopes the new ball can help them do better after the break. Ends by saying Phillips is riding his luck, he has done well though till now but he hopes they can get rid of him early.

Another session which belongs to the Australians! Three wickets in this one too and the Aussies made run-scoring also difficult. They started off by getting rid of Taylor very early. Watling did show some resistance but he fell to an uncharacteristic shot. There was another budding stand between Colin de Grandhomme and Phillips before the former was run out. Now Glenn is the only recognized batter left. He has had a lot of fortune in this short innings of his but the Kiwis will hope he can make it count and continue fighting it out with the tail. Australia on the other hand, will try and bundle the remaining wickets out quickly, probably before the follow-on is avoided and then take a call whether to enforce it or not to. Stay tuned for the last session in a while. For now, Cummins is giving an interview.

Nathan Lyon says more than the injury, he is more frustrated to drop the catch which was quite easy. Further adds Phillips seems to be a copy of Steven Smith and it will be interesting to bowl to him and he is looking forward for the challenge.

That's the last over and the umpire pushes the bails off the stumps! Australia's effort to try and sneak in another over by giving it to Head goes in vain, also, it was an expensive last over before Lunch. The hosts though won't mind as it is a good session for them. Three wickets is what they have managed. Lyon got Blundell early today. Raval and Latham then put up another decent stand before Lyon got Jeet. Immediately after the fall of Raval, Latham perished one short of a half ton. Australia could have had another had Lyon not dropped Phillips of his own bowling. New Zealand though will be relieved that happened and they would want him to make use of the life he got. Also, a lot will be dependent on Taylor here as the Kiwis will want him to play long and the rest to play around him. Can they do so? Will the fightback continue or will the visitors surrender? Join us in a while to find out but for now, the star of the first session, Lyon is giving an interview.

Hello and a warm welcome to Day 3 of the final Test between Australia and New Zealand. Probably for the first time in this series we saw some fight from the visitors. However, they need to keep that going as they are still quite behind in this game. They trail by another 391 runs, that though is secondary as their first aim will be to avoid the follow-on. They would hope the current pair which is set to continue the good work and the rest to also contribute when their chance arrives. Australia, on the other hand, will be looking to pick wickets at regular intervals. The wicket did offer some purchase to the bowlers yesterday. It will be interesting to see how it plays today.
... Day 3, Session 1 ...

Day 2 though was all about Labuschagne and he was the one who led the Australian team off the field. It was the right-hander's effort who took his side to an excellent total. It is because of him the Aussies are ahead in the game at the moment. However, wickets is what they will be needing on Day 3 to strengthen their hold on this game. The wicket is offering some assistance to the spinners so it will be another testing day. Join us for all the action on 5th January 2020 at 1030 local (2330 GMT, Previous Day). Till then, take care and goodbye!

Overall, it has been a good day for the visitors, probably the only day till now in the series where you can give it to the Kiwis. First they managed to take 7 wickets for around 170 runs and then played the last session out without losing a wicket. They have brought down the deficit to below 400 and now with all the 10 wickets in hand, they would hope to do another thing which they haven't so far, that is bat the whole day on Sunday.

A tremendous session for the visitors! A wicketless one, their first wicketless session in this series. The two openers have showed great fight and determination to battle it out and move into Day 3 unscathed.

AUSTRALIA HAVE DECLARED! They have set New Zealand a mammoth target of 416! Why 416 when the lead is 420? Because the penalty runs will be adjusted in the Kiwis' target. But it is an excellent attacking batting display from Australia today morning. Both Warner and Burns played with a very positive approach right from the word go. The two added a 100-run plus stand before Burns fell 10 short of a half ton. Warner though continued along with Labuschagne who also came out all guns blazing. They also notched up another attacking 100-plus stand with the opener scoring a ton and ML scoring yet another half ton. It seemed that the Australians were aiming for the 450-run mark but once Labuschagne got out, Tim Paine decided to declare.

Hello and welcome to the coverage of Day 4 of the final Test between Australia and New Zealand. The scenario is quite simple today, Australia will be looking to score quickly, probably try and bat a session or maybe two and then declare to give their bowlers enough time to bundle the Kiwis out for the second time in the game. New Zealand, on the other hand, need to try and stop the hosts from scoring quickly and try and delay the declaration to as much as possible. An intriguing day of cricket awaits. Stay tuned.
... Day 4, Session 1 ...

Now then! What can we expect on Day 4? Australia upping the ante? New Zealand batting again? Some rain? Probably all three. However, it will be interesting to see how long do Australia bat keeping the forecast in mind! All those questions will be answered on 6th January 2020 at 1030 local (2330 GMT, Previous Day). Till then, take care and goodbye!

Earlier in the day, the Kiwis entered Day 3 with all 10 wickets in hand and hoping they would get close to the Aussie total but they got nowhere close. Nathan Lyon and Pat Cummins were the key for the Aussies with the former taking a 5-fer and the latter a three-fer. Glenn Phillips was the star with the bat for the visitors but a bigger effort was needed from him and the rest too.

End of another day in this Test series and once again, it is the Aussies who are on top. Also, the final session too belongs to them, they wrapped up the Kiwi innings quickly and then head into Day 4 unscathed. The approach by the openers was a sedate one but we will surely see them attack a lot more on Monday.

So that is it from this game and this series. The Kiwis will actually be relieved this is over. They have not only gone through a bad time on the field but also off the field. They though now have time to regroup and prepare for another stern test which awaits as they will be playing India in just less than a months time. The Aussies on the other, hand have dominated the home season in some manner. They can be very pleased with how things have gone for them. However, it is now time for them to take their mind off the longer format as they will be heading to India for an ODI series which will begin in a few weeks. For now though, you can follow the South Africa and England Test or the Big Bash which will begin shortly. Till then, take care and goodbye!

The Trans-Tasman trophy has been handed to Paine and now his teammates have been asked to join him to celebrate. The Australian players are pushing Labuschagne ahead and they went him to lead the side over the podium but he probably is too shy to do so and it is Cummins who goes up the stairs first and then the rest follow. They are now seen posing with the trophy. All happy faces and rightly so.

Victorious Australian skipper, Tim Paine, is jumping and running to give the interview. On the double series whitewash, Paine feels that he is very lucky to be the captain of such a team. Observes that the batting has become very consistent while the pace attack just keeps getting better and better, marvelling at the fact that in spite of Josh Hazlewood injured, there was someone stepping up. Praises Nathan Lyon for his support as well. On Australia's improvement over the last 12 months, Paine believes that they were getting 20 wickets before as well but were not scoring runs - something which has happened in this series and is happy to see the competition. Stresses that in the last 12 months, they were relying too much on too few individuals but this series has probably thrown up a few options. However, he is cautious to say that the away series coming up will be a true test of his team's character. On the contributions by the players to the bushfire victims, Paine says that the group realizes as a whole that the firefighters are doing a tremendous job in trying to save the victims, who are very unfortunate to be a part of those fires. Adds that his team is lucky to be just playing cricket and not be out there, needing to brave the dangers.

New Zealand series skipper (he was not playing this match), Kane Williamson, says that he is feeling much better in terms of health. Praises Australia for their clinical display, right from the first Test of the series which pushed New Zealand on the back foot, from where they were never able to recover. Hopes to take the learnings from this series into the future. On being asked to point the weak links, Kane says that it is not just one thing but plenty as Australia outplayed them in all departments. For starters, he says that his bowlers were not able to get wickets in clusters and then with the bat, they could not forge partnerships. Wants the individuals in his group to regroup and come back collectively as a stronger unit. Feels fantastic, he says, to see the depth in the Kiwi squad and as a captain, to have so many options. Admits that plenty of guys in his side were playing in Australia for the first time, so it was very tough, very disappointing and very frustrating. Feels that after months of terrific work before this series, they did have hopes of doing well here but sadly, it did not pan out that way.

MARNUS LABUSCHAGNE HAS BEEN NAMED THE PLAYER OF THE MATCH AND THE SERIES. Feels that it has been an amazing summer for him and his team - the bowlers and the batsmen, coming together as a group. On getting his maiden double Test ton in front of his family, he thanks them for their infinite support which has helped him get thus far and also thanks them for coming here to watch him play. On the reason for his success, Marnus feels that he has learnt to concentrate harder and not commit silly mistakes. On the upcoming tour to India, ML believes that it is going to be a great opportunity, IF he gets the opportunity to play there.

David Warner is now up for a chat with Kath Loughnan. Credits the team for starting the summer the way they did and then build it against Pakistan and finally end it here. Praises Nathan Lyon for the way he answered his critics. On his own ton in this Test, David says that he always maintained that he was never out of form and was hitting the ball well in the nets. Feels that the hard work just paid off and is happy to have contributed to the Jane McGrath cause. On Pattinson's catch, Warner laughs and says that he was actually comparing it to the one taken by Glenn McGrath in 2004/05. On Joe Burns' contribution, Warner admits that Joe Burns has not quite done well as per his expectations but expects him to bounce back hard, since there is the Big Bash to follow and later on, the Sheffield Shield before the tour to Bangladesh.

Kath Loughnan is interviewing Nathan Lyon. On Australia becoming the number 2 Test side, Nathan Lyon feels very happy to see the team getting back to the top slowly. On his own bowling, 'Gary' says that it is a special feeling to perform well in front of his own crowd. Feels even more special to have contributed to the Jane McGrath cause. Lyon says that there is a good gelling within the group and they want to be the number 1 side in the world but admits that there is a lot of work to be done prior to that.

The Kiwis had another opportunity to show their mettle, nobody expected them to chase this down but at least they were expected to make the Aussies work hard for the wickets but that was once again not the case. They were bundled out for a mere 136 within 47.5 overs with Lyon once again bagging a fifer.

The hosts though decided not to enforce the follow-on and they played an attacking brand of cricket. Batted for around two and a half sessions before declaring. Warner's ton was the highlight and because of him and Labuschagne's half ton, the Aussies gave the visitors a huge target.

In reply, the Kiwis started off well, they had a wicket-less session on Day 2 and it gave the feeling that their battling line-up has finally arrived and they might just give Australia a run for their money but that was not the case. The Aussies bowlers were all over them on Day 3 and blew them away even before they could avoid the follow-on. Nathan Lyon and Pat Cummins were the tormentor-in-chief with the offie taking a fifer.

The story has been the same right from the Day 1 of this series and it continues to be the same in this Test too. Australia dominated this game right from the word go. They won the toss, elected to bat, posted a huge total on a wicket which was not that easy to score. Marnus Labuschagne was the star for them with the bat with a double ton.

To be honest this series has been a real disappointment, everybody expected it to be a cracker but New Zealand have surrendered in all the three Tests. Even in this one, let alone the margin of defeat but the manner in which they were beaten was actually embarrassing. A little less than two sessions is what they had to play out to take it into Day 5 but they failed to do that too. Except for Watling and Colin de Grandhomme no batter showed any fight. The rest just had no answers to this excellent Australian bowling attack.

The teams are seen shaking hands which means that Matt Henry won't be coming out to bat. Australia have won the Test match, they have completed the whitewash and it is another emphatic victory for them. They have blown away the visitors for the third time in a row!

Full and down the leg side, Watling sweeps it but hits it straight to Pat Cummins at short backward square leg. The catch is taken and that is it. AUSTRALIA WIN BY 279 RUNS AND SWEEP THE SERIES 3-0!

OUT! BOWLED! Lock, stock and barrell. That is a Mitchell Starc special. Tail-enders and fast bowlers. Special relation. Keep targetting the body and then the stumps. Give them a whiff that you are going to hurt them by banging it in. Keep pegging them on the back foot and then fire in a yorker. Right at the base of the stumps. The woodwork is shattered. 15 minutes left for the close today. Guess the game will be extended by 30 minutes if New Zealand don't get bowled out before the allotted time of Stumps.

OUT! CAUGHT! Why would you play this shot when there are 20 minutes left for Stumps? Very very uncharacteristic from Todd Astle. Is he the same Astle who faced 95 balls for his 25 in the first innings? Brain fade. Flighted delivery outside off, Astle looks to play the slog sweep, aiming to drag it but gets a top edge. Now, initially, it looks like the ball will land in between. Short mid-wicket runs back while James Pattinson at mid on rushes to his right. He gives it a good chase, clearly indicating that he wants to go for the catch. Keeps his eyes on the ball and then dives full stretch to his right to take a stunner. Superbly done. 23 minutes left on Day 4, Australia need 3 wickets. Or 2, if Matt Henry does not bat.

Todd Astle is the new man in.

OUT! CAUGHT! Oh dear... 40 minutes to go to Stumps and Colin de Grandhomme throws is away. He cannot control himself. Loopy delivery on middle, de Grandhomme comes down the track and looks to go over the leg side. However, he does not get to the pitch of the ball. It goes off the inner half of the bat and lobs towards deep mid-wicket. There are three men stationed for the catch - deep square leg, deep mid-wicket and long on. Joe Burns gets across to his left from deep mid-wicket while long on rushes to his right. In the end, Burns calls for it and takes it comfortably. This is what happens when you want to play your natural game. Becomes very difficult to understand when to curb your instincts. Still, a pretty decent innings to conclude a difficult tour of Australia. 4 wickets as per the scorecard needed for Australia, but 3, if Matt Henry does not bat. 40 minutes left. Do they have enough time?

Taylor departs almost immediately after he breaks the record of the leading run-scorer for New Zealand in Tests. Half the side back in the hut for the Kiwis.

We are back for the final session of Day 4 and could probably be the final session of the match too. The Australian players are out in the middle. Ross Taylor and BJ Watling will resume their innings for the visitors. Nathan Lyon will start the proceedings for the final session of Day 4.
... Day 4, Session 3 ...

What a session for Australia! First they scored some quick runs and declared and then have blown away the top order of the Kiwis! They are all over the visitors at the moment and are surely sensing a victory today itself. Starc and Lyon have been tormentors-in-chief. Starc took two at the start and Lyon took the other two. New Zealand though have their best batter, Ross Taylor out there and he is partnered by Watling. Both need to fight it out and at least take this game in Day 5. Can they do so? We will find out in a bit.
